-Create cluster
  kind create cluster --name cluster-0 --config=config.yaml
  kubectl cluster info
  kubectl cluster-info --context kind-cluster-0 --> kind-<clusterName>
  kubectl get nodes -<get nodes active>

=====================================================
### Namespace (Kubernetes) — Short Note

A namespace is a logical partition inside a Kubernetes cluster used to organize and isolate workloads.
Resources like sql, nginx and its Deployments, pod and Services can be namespaced

What can be namespaced:

 Pods
 Deployments / ReplicaSets
 Services
 ConfigMaps
 Secrets
 Jobs / CronJobs

(Not namespaced: Nodes, PersistentVolumes, StorageClasses, CRDs)

Why namespaces are used:

 Avoid name collisions (same app name in different namespaces)
 Separate environments (dev / staging / prod)
 Enforce access control with RBAC
 Apply resource limits using quotas
 Enable safe cleanup (delete a namespace → delete everything inside)

> Namespaces isolate workloads and policies, not nodes or infrastructure.

kubectl get namespace
kubectl get pods -<lists pods in namespace, default ns by default>
kubectl get pods -n kube-system -<pods are here

kubectl get ns
→ Lists all namespaces in the cluster.

kubectl run nginx --image=nginx
→ Creates and runs an nginx pod in the default namespace.

kubectl get pods -n nginx
→ Lists pods in the nginx namespace.

kubectl get pods
→ Lists pods in the default namespace.

kubectl delete pod nginx
→ Deletes the nginx pod from the default namespace.

kubectl run nginx --image=nginx -n nginx
→ Creates and runs an nginx pod in the nginx namespace.

kubectl get pods
→ Lists pods in the default namespace.

kubectl get pods -n nginx
→ Lists pods in the nginx namespace.

kubectl delete pod nginx -n nginx
→ Deletes the nginx pod from the nginx namespace.

kubectl apply -f namespace.yml -<create and apply and create ns from manifest file>

kctl describe pod/nginx-pod -n nginx

=========================
### DEPLOYEMENT - manager for replica sets

A ReplicaSet makes sure N identical Pods are always running.-if pod dies, Creates, no rolling update, rollback or versioning (created and owned by Deployments)

Labels (app: nginx) → tags put on the pods so Kubernetes can identify and group them.

Selector (matchLabels: app: nginx) → tells the Deployment which pods it owns and manages by matching their labels.

Template → the pod blueprint the ReplicaSet uses to create new pods when scaling or replacing failures.

- k get deploy -n nginx
-  k scale deployment/nginx-deployment -n nginx --replicas=3
-  kubectl get pods -n nginx -o wide


ROLLOUT: kubectl set image deployment/<deployment-name> -n <namespace> <container-name>=<new-image-name>:<tag> [options]

  <deployment-name>: 
      The name of the specific Deployment you want to modify (e.g., nginx-deployment).

  <container-name>:
      The name of the container within the Deployment's Pod template to update.

  <new-image-name>:<tag>: 
      The full name and tag of the new container image (e.g., nginx:1.23.1)

Does a rolling update, old containers are still up while new ones spin up

READ ABOUT ANNOTATIONS

====================
REPLICASET : cant rollout update, no down time, etc: 
k get replicaset -n <namespace>

===================

DAEMONSETS: Ensures every worker node/selected worker has one replica
no replica needed to be specified in manifest


